[h1]Dead by Daylight aka Hide & Seek for Barely Functioning Adults[/h1]

[b]PROS:[/b]

+ Pretty cool, spooky visual presentation ;
+ Well placed sound effects ;
+ Great execution of an inherently difficult concept that is the asymmetric online game ;
+ Smooth and accessible, yet deeply strategic and thrilling gameplay ;
+ Sizable roster of both killers and survivors, as well as a large variety of perks and alternatives to build and customise your character ;
+ Captivating meta ;
+ Content being added on a regular basis ;
+ Developers actually care about balancing and improving the experience for their players.

[b]CONS:[/b]

- Low skill cap ;
- Updates occasionally mess up the game a bit (perks malfunction, jarring visual bugs, among others).

________________________________

I started playing Dead by Daylight about a year and a half ago on a free weekend and ended up getting the game and all the DLC right away. DbD is basically hide & seek for adults - a concept which, admittedly, has me sold by default. To play, first you choose a role (either killer or survivor) and then select a character from the generous (and growing) roster. The gist of it: as a survivor you must fix 5 generators to power up 2 gates so you can open them and run away. As a killer you must keep the survivors from accomplishing this, chasing and slashing them, hooking them on meat hooks and so on, and so forth. Besides a number of alternative possibilities to achieve "winning conditions" which you will learn by playing the game, the catch is that everyone has perks, which are traits akin to superpowers. New players will plow through a bunch of hours before they understand why others manage to do some of the things they do. For that reason it is very important to get to know the perks, so take your time. Everything falls into place once you get to know the game. Most of the content is accessible without the purchase of any DLC's too, which is to say you can grind for most of the characters and respective perks instead of buying them. Aside from minor design choices and bugs, my only real issue with the game resides in its skill ceiling. Maybe I've just grown too used to online games in which 300 hours of playtime are barely enough to give you a proper chance at higher ranks, but I just wish that after 300 something hours I didn't feel like I've dealt with pretty much everything this game can throw at you... here's hoping they keep putting out content, including the fabled brand new mode the community has been craving so much.

If any of this sounds good to you and with the amount of effort being put into improving the game constantly, as well as a thriving community both in and out of the game (shout-out official DbD subreddit), you should be in for at least a couple hundred hours of quality entertainment with this game. With that, I'll say that Dead by Daylight has seen me through some of my darkest days. The whole vibe around the game is awesome and though there's definitely some room for improvement in the game in general, no other game currently in the market accomplishes what DbD does.

I wholeheartedly recommend this game.

8.0/10
